the recognition of the Federation as a full member of the United Nations (UN). This is significant for various reasons. First, the transition from the FSM Trust Territory relationship to the formal Geneva relationship through the adoption of the FSM Constitution on November 3rd, 1978 has always been a protracted process until the culmination of this transition. Second, the effort to have Micronesia recognized as independent gears to the establishment of the FSM, hence, stress the recognition of independence has been a corrupted statement that has been circled that conflates political independence with nation sovereignty. Sadly, as many politicos have said “cheating from independence is anti-self-determination”, and further devalues the status of the FSM. This misunderstanding has created a divisive national mood, especially since the FSM came into the international community. Full Membership in the United Nations affords Micronesia a seat in the larger and wider body of nations with pursuits for international peace and universal justice, and establishes Micronesia as a nation with no inferiority complex on self-identity, purpose, and pride. The United Nations has become the guardian of international peace and is as important life that stands for justice, says its Secretary General in one of his numerous trips around the world calling for greater respect of human rights and international justice, and in the most recent commemoration through Oral Histories of fallen UN peacekeepers who patronized Yemen in February 2016.
